This section is for objects so we only have == and !=.   You are thinking about comparable and Numbers.   Those comparisons are both located elsewhere.   

Numbers is a delegated comparison with the one exception of null pointers. (again we only have EQ and NE in that limited case)
```
static PyObject *PyJPNumberLong_compare(PyObject *self, PyObject *other, int op)
{
        JP_PY_TRY("PyJPNumberLong_compare");
        JPContext *context = PyJPModule_getContext();
        JPJavaFrame frame(context);
        if (isNull(self))
        {
                if (op == Py_EQ)
                        return PyBool_FromLong(other == Py_None);
                if (op == Py_NE)
                        return PyBool_FromLong(other != Py_None);
                PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError, "'%s' not supported with null pointer", op_names[op]);
                JP_RAISE_PYTHON();
        }
        return PyLong_Type.tp_richcompare(self, other, op);
        JP_PY_CATCH(NULL);
}
```

And for Comparable it is currently in Python
```
@_jcustomizer.JImplementationFor('java.lang.Comparable')
class _JComparable(object):

    def __eq__(self, o):
        return self.compareTo(o) == 0

    def __ne__(self, o):
        return self.compareTo(o) != 0

    def __gt__(self, o):
        return self.compareTo(o) > 0

    def __lt__(self, o):
        return self.compareTo(o) < 0

    def __ge__(self, o):
        return self.compareTo(o) >= 0

    def __le__(self, o):
        return self.compareTo(o) <= 0

    __hash__ = _jpype._JObject.__hash__
```

So if this was for comparable then a switch would definitely be warranted as we have a lot of cases to cover.  But java.lang.Object is pretty limited.  In general we are using the Python method resolution, thus we hide methods by implementing them on derived classes.  That does lead to some confusion.

That said is it a very good idea that we need to investigate comparable for the same bug as the object one.  It likely throws NullPointerException.   My question is what should be the correct behavior for LE, LT, GT, and GE when one or both the pointer are null.  I will tag this in the issue tracker and get back to it a bit later.  I am trying to not push all of the JPype code back into the CPython layer if possible, but there are some things like this horrible equals logic that are just too huge and slow if written in Python.

