So, a user's `register.py` would likely look like this:

```python
def rules():
  return [UnionRule(python_tgt, TypeChecked) for python_tgt in [PythonBinary, PythonLibrary, Pythontests])
```

> Also... remind me why we need to wrap/unwrap? Was it for perf reasons? Is it that much better?

There two parts here:

1. We unwrap before we call into a kernel for performance reasons. Whenever perform any operation on a datapoint, `__torch_function__` is invoked. This will even happen multiple times if the the operation is one that retains the type, like `.clone()`. IIRC, we are talking about low double digit microseconds here. However, this is not needed for functionality.
2. We wrap the output of the kernel to retain the input type of the dispatcher. Basically if you put in a `BoundingBox` you also want to have one back rather than a simple tensor. Otherwise, we force the user to always wrap by themselves in between calls.

> The datapoint_warpping logic (and the rest) should be kept outside of the registration mechanism IMO. I understand it makes it convenient to have the wrapping here, but these are 2 very distinct concepts.
> 
> The wrapping logic should probably just be a different decorator.

Although I agree that these are two concepts and should be kept separate, I don't think we can. The wrapping must only happen for when the kernel is called from a dispatcher, but not when called directly. Meaning

```python
@register_kernel(resize, datapoints.Image)
@default_datapoint_wrapping
def resize_image_tensor(...)
    ...
```

is wrong, since now calling `resize_image_tensor` will also try to wrap although it shouldn't. It will also fail if we pass a plain tensor, since the re-wrapping on the way back requires the input to be a datapoint.

The only way to go with two decorators is to never actually register a kernel, but always an intermediate function:

```python
@register_kernel(resize, datapoints.Image)
@default_datapoint_wrapping
def _resize_image_tensor_dispatch(...)
    return resize_image_tensor(...)
```

That would basically mean that we just move exactly what we have on the methods now as functions into functional modules. IMHO this is too much boilerplate to justify keeping both functionalities separate. Plus, we also need to find a new name for `register_kernels` in that case, because what we register doesn't really fit our definition or kernel anymore.

