TO adaptor node affinity with labels,  I suggest the following two options:  
The current new_labels and affinity_constraints cannot fully express node affinity, and the following expressions are required.

**Options 1:**
```
message ResourceBundle {
  map<string, double> resources = 1;
  repeated LabelMatchExpression node_affinity_expressions = 2;
}

enum LabelMatchOperator {
  IN = 0;
  NOT_IN = 1;
  EXISTS = 2;
  DOES_NOT_EXIST = 3;
}

message LabelMatchExpression {
  string key = 1;
  LabelMatchOperator label_match_operator = 2;
  repeated string values = 3;
  bool soft = 4;
}

```


**Options 2:**
```
message ResourceBundle {
  map<string, double> resources = 1;
  SchedulingStrategy scheduling_strategy = 2;
}

enum LabelMatchOperator {
  IN = 0;
  NOT_IN = 1;
  EXISTS = 2;
  DOES_NOT_EXIST = 3;
}

message LabelMatchExpression {
  string key = 1;
  LabelMatchOperator label_match_operator= 2;
  repeated string values = 3;
  bool soft = 4;
}

message NodeAffinitySchedulingStrategy {
  repeated LabelMatchExpression match_expressions = 1;
}

message SchedulingStrategy {
  oneof scheduling_strategy {
    // Default hybrid scheduling strategy.
    DefaultSchedulingStrategy default_scheduling_strategy = 1;
    // Placement group based scheduling strategy.
    PlacementGroupSchedulingStrategy placement_group_scheduling_strategy = 2;
    // Best effort spread scheduling strategy.
    SpreadSchedulingStrategy spread_scheduling_strategy = 3;
    NodeAffinitySchedulingStrategy node_affinity_scheduling_strategy = 4;
  }
}
```

@abtink Thanks! One thing still to consider is how would a Router with many children handle the multiple Answer messages? Frame buffer / queue space is limited and I think the Thread spec text prescribes the device to apply "backpressure" i.e. stop sending further Answers if the frame queue reaches a certain size or frame age (? not sure).

Ideally it would be best if the client would be in control using a request/response type protocol, as e.g. CoAP blockwise is also using - each next block is explicitly fetched by the client. That also reduces DoS opportunities e.g. sending a small request frame could cause an avalanche of data on the mesh.

Further thoughts: Also in CoAP blockwise, instead of a "Query ID TLV" the Token value is used as the identifier of the transaction. Not sure if we really need to reinvent all such mechanisms here?   The main problem of "Blockwise" is that it assumes one data blob is fetched and that data can be arbitrarily divided into blocks of certain sizes (32/64/128 etc).  That's not compatible with our model here.

