jeroenterheerdt@, I found a (hacky) solution to get motion, ding events locally saved and accessible thru HA. Somehow when Ring gets a motion or ding event, it rejects or at least makes the Sip session for recording gone crazy and never returned. At the end, I couldn't get it reliable/work to call it from HA with Python. So, I wrote/copied typescript and run separately with Node catching all events and ask it to record until it successful identified by Ring id. It seems the Ring id is the same for events occurred relatively at the same time period. Well, here is the ts file I made (or rather copies with modifies from the examples):

```
import { RingApi } from 'ring-client-api'
import * as path from 'path'

async function example(myemail,mypassword,outputdir,duration) {
  const ringApi = new RingApi({
      // Replace with your ring email/password
      email: myemail,
      password: mypassword,
      // Refresh token is used when 2fa is on
      // refreshToken: refresh_token,
      debug: true,
      cameraDingsPollingSeconds: 2
    }),
    [camera] = await ringApi.getCameras()

  if (!camera) {
    console.log('No cameras found')
    return
  }

  const express = require('express')
  const serveIndex = require('serve-index')
  const app = express()

  app.use(express.static(outputdir))
  app.use(serveIndex(outputdir, {'icons': true, 'view': 'details', 'fileList': 'name'}))
  app.use('/ring', express.static(outputdir))
  app.use('/ring', serveIndex(outputdir, {'icons': true, 'view': 'details', 'fileList': 'name'}))
  app.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log(
      'Listening on port 3000.'
    )
  })

  console.log('Doorbots connection: ' + camera.data.alerts.connection)
  var ring_event_id: string = ''
  camera.onNewDing.subscribe(ding => {
    const event =
      ding.kind == 'motion'
        ? 'motion'
        : ding.kind == 'ding'
        ? 'ding'
        : `Video started (${ding.kind})`
    console.log(
      `${event} on ${camera.name} camera. Ding id ${
        ding.id_str
      }.  Received at ${new Date()}`
    )
    const event_ts = new Date()
    const ring_event_id = ding.id_str
    const output_file = path.join(
      outputdir,
      event_ts.getFullYear() + "-" + event_ts.toLocaleDateString('en-US', {month: '2-digit'}) + "-" + event_ts.getDate() +
      "_" +
      event_ts.getHours().toString().padStart(2, '0') + "-" +
      event_ts.getMinutes().toString().padStart(2, '0') + "-" +
      ring_event_id +
      "_" + 'part0.mp4')
    const fs = require('fs')

    try {
      if (!fs.existsSync(output_file)) {
        console.log(output_file)
        camera.recordToFile(output_file, duration)
      } else {
        console.log('Already on Recording for: ' + output_file)
      }
    } catch(err) { 
      console.error(err)
    }
  })
  console.log('Listening for motion and doorbell presses on your cameras.')
}
// print process.argv
var args = process.argv.slice(2);
//email is args[0]
//password is args[1]
//outputdir is args[2]
//duration is args[3]
var email = args[0]
var password = args[1]
var outputdir = args[2]
var duration = args[3]

example(email, password, outputdir, duration)
```

So, motion and ding events are saved in [outputdir]. All the files are accessible (listed) thru http://localhost:3000. So, I put in HA Ring component with the above modified `camera.py` to show the latest video (and snapshot). Then use Panel iFrame in HA to access http://localhost:3000  for all the records. Well, actually, I use apache ProxyPass to map back the localhost:3000 to https web access point and put in HA (https) Panel iFrame. Looking forward a better, Python/HA native support.

