I believe that this `formatted_print` call is the correct place to handle the case where the user is already a member of the group.

Here's an example of the full response data:
```json
{
  "add": [],
  "errors": {
    "add": [
      {
        "code": "ALREADY_ACTIVE",
        "detail": "The identity is already an active member of the group.",
        "identity_id": "c699d42e-d274-11e5-bf75-1fc5bf53bb24"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

We may want more sophisticated behavior in the future, but for now I think the correct approach is for the CLI to treat this type of response as an error condition. We could raise a `ValueError`, or a custom error class -- either would be acceptable. That will get us a relatively clean `exit(1)` plus a message.

It's okay to try to unpack the `"detail"` and `"code"` fields, but please assume if you do so that the fields may not be present. I don't know if it's possible in fact for a response to come back which doesn't populate `"add"` in the main response body and also doesn't populate `"errors"`, but it's at least possible in theory.

