Here, we are defining `NetworkKey` as a sub-class of `otNetworkKey` and also add additional member variables `mCryptoType` and `mKeyRef` to the `NetworkKey`.

In the code (e.g., in `thread_api.cpp` in `otThreadSetNetworkKey()`) there are situation where we cast from an `otNetworkKey` instance (base type instance) and treat it as `NetworkKey` which would not be correct then. I highly advice against this model (even if we won't be using the extra member variable on sub-class after casting, it is not a good idea to do so and it easy to make a mistake here).

-----

The general model we use in OT:
- The public OT API and type definition are all C based (say `otIp6Address` defined as `struct` and are all PoD (or standard layout).
- Then inside OT core, we define a C++ class equivalent (say `Ip6::Address` which adds methods on the type, but never add new member variable.
- This then allows us to safely cast between the C definitions and C++ core equivalents.

I highly suggest we continue to follow same model, i.e. `NetworkKey` should be mirror `otNetworkKey` and contain no additional data fields.

 If we need additional member variable we can considering defining a new class/type which is not a sub-class of `otNetworKey` but can store either a `NetworKkey or a `KeyRef` and we provide methosd to set it from a given `NetworKey` or `KeyRef`. For example:

```c++
typedef otNetworkKeyRef NetworkKeyRef;

class NetworkKeyInfo
{
public:
    void SetFrom(NetworkKey &aKey);
    void SetFrom(NetworkKeyRef aKeyRef);

    Mac::CryptoType  mCryptoType;
    NetworkKey       mLiteralKey;
    NetworkKeyRef    mKeyRef;
};
```

